<h2 class="section-head">Roasting and <em>Brewing Recommendations</em></h2>

<p class="body">Honey-process coffee roasts best at City+ to Full City, roughly the same window as a clean natural. That range develops the sugars enough to expose the stone-fruit and brown-sugar character without pushing into the roast-forward territory that buries origin flavor. Avoid French roast or any heavily charred development: the sweetness that defines the method evaporates above Full City, and what remains is just generic dark roast bitterness with none of the payoff.</p>

<p class="body">For brewing, pour-over and drip both perform extremely well. The medium-to-full body of honey process means it does not need the heavier extraction of a French press to feel substantial in the cup. A standard V60 or Kalita Wave pour with a medium grind, water at 200 to 205 degrees Fahrenheit, and a 1:16 ratio will surface the stone fruit cleanly. Drip brewers do almost as well with less attention.</p>

<p class="body">Espresso is where honey-process coffee genuinely excels and is underused. Pulled as a single origin or used as a base in a blend, honey-process beans bring built-in sweetness to the shot that washed coffees simply do not have. A Costa Rican yellow honey pulled as a 1:2 espresso ratio produces a syrupy, peach-and-honeycomb shot that needs no added sugar even for drinkers who normally take it. For milk drinks, honey-process espresso adds caramel depth that pairs beautifully with steamed whole milk.</p>

